quial speech in ways that can be difficult to analyze. In this groundbreaking collection edited by Michael G. Lacy and Kent A. Ono, scholars seek to examine this complicated and contradictory terrain while moving the field of communication in a more intellectually productive direction. An outstanding group of contributors from a range of academic backgrounds challenges traditional definitions and applications of rhetoric. From the troubling media representations of black looters after Hurricane Katrina and rhetoric in news coverage about the Columbine and Virginia Tech massacres to cinematic representations of race in Crash, Blood Diamond, and Quentin Tarantino's films, these essays reveal complex intersections and constructions of racialized bodies and discourses, critiquing race in innovative and exciting ways. Critical Rhetorics of Race seeks not only to understand and navigate a world fraught with racism, but to change it, one word at a time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aRacism in mass media. 0aRacism in motion pictures. 0aRacism in popular culture. 0aRacism in sports. 0aRacismxUnited States. 0aRacismzUnited States. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, Carol W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalafell, Bernadette Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriffin, Rachel Alicia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalualani, Rona Tamiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHasian, Marouf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaspel, Kathleen C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g